solution: ```class Solution {
    public int subarrayGCD(int[] nums, int k) {
        int n = nums.length, count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            int g = 0;
            for (int j = i; j < n; ++j) {
                g = gcd(g, nums[j]);
                if (g == k) ++count;
                else if (g < k) break;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
    private int gcd(int a, int b) {
        while (b != 0) {
            int tmp = b;
            b = a % b;
            a = tmp;
        }
        return a;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n² log U) where U is the maximum value in nums
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Iterate over every subarray start index, extend rightwards while maintaining the running GCD. When the GCD drops below k, further extensions cannot recover, so we break early. This pruning plus the small input size (n ≤ 1000) makes the quadratic scan fast and energy-efficient.

